TY  - JOUR
AU  - Plantin, Guillaume
T1  - Shadow Banking and Bank Capital Regulation
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhu055
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 146
EP  - 175
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Banks are subject to capital requirements because their privately optimal leverage is higher than the socially optimal one. This is in turn because banks fail to internalize all costs that their insolvency creates for agents who use their money-like liabilities to settle transactions. If banks can bypass capital regulation in an opaque shadow banking sector, it may be optimal to relax capital requirements so that liquidity dries up in the shadow banking sector. Tightening capital requirements may spur a surge in shadow banking activity that leads to an overall larger risk on the money-like liabilities of the formal and shadow banking institutions.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhu055
ER  - 



